{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491617"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:55:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:55:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"999"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/999"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.09,0.03,0.8,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"999"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40119"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/999"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"999"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24832"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"548"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"255"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33538"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42195"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/40119"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old man presents with a nodule on his back, which has been present for 12 months. He thinks it is slowly getting larger. He has no other health issues. On examination there is a 1 cm red, translucent nodule on his back (image). Nothing else abnormal is found.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cryotherapy","Topical fluorouracil","Intralesional imiquimod","Surgical excision with 4mm margin","Watch and wait"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe photograph shows an ulcerated translucent nodule with a pearly rolled edge with surface telangiectasia. This is the characteristic appearance of a basal cell carcinoma (BCC). These are locally invasive non-melanocytic tumours with very low metastatic potential. There are multiple subtypes of BCC, less aggressive subtypes include superficial and nodular BCC. The more aggressive subtypes which tends to infiltrate to involve deeper tissue with higher risk of recurrence include infiltrative, morpheic and micronodular BCC. Nodular BCCs classically appear as skin coloured nodules with surface telangiectasia and a pearly rolled edge. Although BCCs have low metastatic spread, they can be locally invasive and should be treated with the same respect as other skin cancers. \u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical excision\u003C/strong\u003E remains to be the gold standard for treatment of BCCs. Superficial BCC is the only subtype where alternate non-surgical treatment options including topical imiquimod, cryotherapy or photodynamic therapy could be considered. All other subtypes of BCCs should be removed with minimal surgical margin of 4-6 mm depending on its risk profile. This BCC would be considered a low risk given site (low risk site), nodular subtype (low risk) and hence, does not require a large margin. A margin of 1cm is often reserved for malignancies including melanoma and high risk SCCs. Watch and wait would be inappropriate as this lesion has concerning features on examination. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In general, basal cell carcinomas should be treated by local excision."],"references":["Brandt MG, Moore CC. Nonmelanoma Skin Cancer. Facial Plast Surg Clin N Am 2019; 27:1-13."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24832"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"999"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14561"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14561"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eb881f00-92bc-468e-bd2d-cc8037235a1f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eb881f00-92bc-468e-bd2d-cc8037235a1f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":733,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/24832"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-10-30T20:09:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-10-30T20:09:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"999"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40119"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type